title: Update on monitoring COVID-19 vaccination
content_text: As at 8pm on December 5, around 9.54 million doses of COVID-19 vaccines had been administered for members of the public. Around 4.78 million people had received at least one dose of vaccine, accounting for 71.0 per cent of the population aged 12 or above. The DH received 6 461 reports (Note 1) of adverse events (0.07 per cent of the total vaccine doses administered). Among the death cases concerning persons who had been vaccinated, including 50 cases (Note 2) with vaccination within 14 days before they passed away (0.0005

(Note 2) with vaccination within 14 days before they passed away (0.0005 per cent of the total vaccine doses administered), none of the death cases was associated with vaccination. As at December 5, the Expert Committee on Clinical Events Assessment Following COVID-19 Immunisation (Expert Committee) had concluded that 35 death cases had no causal relationship with vaccination, and preliminarily considered that 14 cases were not associated with vaccination. One case is still pending further information for assessment. In addition to the aforesaid adverse events, the Expert Committee also reviews events of special interests following vaccination which are serious and may

adverse events, the Expert Committee also reviews events of special interests following vaccination which are serious and may have potential causal relationship with vaccination for continuous stringent monitoring and further specific assessment to ascertain whether these events had any causal relationship with vaccination. At the most recent meeting, the Expert Committee reviewed events of special interests following vaccination, including a death case with suspected myocarditis which occurred over 14 days after receiving the Comirnaty vaccine. The causal relationship of that case with vaccination has been concluded to be indeterminate. Details of the case will be included in the "Report on the Safety Monitoring of COVID-19 Vaccines in Hong Kong" to be

in the "Report on the Safety Monitoring of COVID-19 Vaccines in Hong Kong" to be issued on Friday (December 10). The Expert Committee considered that there is no unusual pattern identified so far, and will continue to closely monitor the relevant situation and collect data for assessment. According to information from the HA, during the period from November 8 to December 5, the ratio of death cases out of those without a vaccination record was 129.9 cases for every 100 000 people, whereas the ratio of death cases for those with a vaccination record was 7.2 cases for every 100 000 people.

Out of those without a vaccination record, the ratio of death cases with acute stroke or acute myocardial infarction was 5.9 cases for every 100 000 people, whereas the ratio of death cases under the same category for those with a vaccination record was 0.8 cases for every 100 000 people. Furthermore, the ratio of miscarriage cases out of those without a vaccination record was 34.7 cases for every

ratio of miscarriage cases out of those without a vaccination record was 34.7 cases for every 100 000 people, whereas the ratio of miscarriage cases for those who had a vaccination record was 13.4 cases for every 100 000 people. Based on the statistical analysis of the above figures, there is no evidence that vaccination increases the risk of death or miscarriage for recipients. The relevant reference statistics will be uploaded to the thematic website for the COVID-19 Vaccination Programme. The majority of non-death cases of adverse events received so far are relatively minor cases. The relevant details can be found in the "Report

adverse events received so far are relatively minor cases. The relevant details can be found in the "Report on the Safety Monitoring of COVID-19 Vaccines in Hong Kong" (www.drugoffice.gov.hk/eps/do/en/doc/Safety_Monitoring_of_COVID-19_Vaccines_in_Hong_Kong.pdf). "The COVID-19 vaccination rate for the elderly aged 80 or above in Hong Kong

"The COVID-19 vaccination rate for the elderly aged 80 or above in Hong Kong is only around 19 per cent at present, meaning that 81 per cent of the elderly in that age group are in a dangerous situation, which is alarming. The Comirnaty and CoronaVac vaccines are highly effective in preventing severe cases and deaths from COVID-19. They can provide effective protection to those vaccinated in preventing serious complications and even deaths after infection. The Government continues to call on persons who are not yet vaccinated, especially senior citizens, chronic patients and other immunocompromised persons who face a much higher chance of death after

citizens, chronic patients and other immunocompromised persons who face a much higher chance of death after COVID-19 infection, to get vaccinated as early as possible for better self-protection before the fifth wave strikes Hong Kong," a Government spokesman said. Note 1: Provisional figures. In the preceding week till 11.59pm on December 5, the DH received one report of suspected myocarditis or pericarditis involving an adolescent in the age group of 12 to 15. The case involved one male aged 14. He experienced chest pains within two days after receiving the first dose of the

male aged 14. He experienced chest pains within two days after receiving the first dose of the Comirnaty vaccine. His condition is stable. Note 2: In the preceding week till 11.59pm on December 5, the DH received two death reports involving individuals who had received COVID-19 vaccination within 14 days before passing away. The cases involved a female aged 82 and a male aged 57. There is no clinical evidence that the incidents arose from vaccination.
